{"parse":{"title":"loaf","pageid":54711,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"==English==\n[[Image:Breads.jpg|thumb|Two loaves (1) of [[bread]]]]\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/ləʊf/|a=RP}}\n** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-loaf.wav|a=Southern England}}\n* {{IPA|en|/loʊf/|a=GenAm}}\n* {{rhymes|en|əʊf|s=1}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{etymon|en|id=block of bread|:inh|enm:lof<id:loaf>|tree=1}}\n* From {{inh|en|enm|laf}}, {{m|enm|lof}}, {{m|enm|loof}}, from {{inh|en|ang|hlāf|t=bread; loaf}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*hlaib}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*hlaibaz|t=bread; loaf}}, of {{unc|en|nocap=1}} origin. Perhaps related to {{cog|ang|hlifian|t=to stand out prominently, tower up}}. \n{{col-top|2|cog}}\nCognate with {{cog|de|Laib|t=loaf}}, {{cog|da,sv|lev|t=loaf}}, {{cog|fo|leivur|t=an oblong bun}}, {{cog|is|hleifur|t=loaf}}, {{cog|nn|leiv|t=loaf}}, {{cog|got|𐌷𐌻𐌰𐌹𐌱𐍃}}, {{m|got|𐌷𐌻𐌰𐌹𐍆𐍃|t=bread}} (whence {{cog|sla-pro|*xlěbъ|t=bread}} (see there for further descendants)), {{cog|et|leib|t=black bread}}, {{cog|fi|leipä|t=bread; loaf}}; also {{cog|lv|klaips|t=loaf}}, {{cog|lt|kliẽpas|t=loaf}}. {{doublet|en|chleb|khleb}}.\n* {{sense|brain or head}} Rhyming slang, {{ellipsis|en|loaf of bread|nocap=1}}.\n{{col-bottom}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun|loaves}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|bread}} {{q|also {{m|en|loaf of bread}}}} A [[block]] of [[bread]] after [[bake|baking]].\n#* {{RQ:Lincoln Pratt's Patients|chapter=8|passage=Philander went into the next room{{...}}and came back with a salt mackerel that dripped brine like a rainstorm. Then he put the coffee pot on the stove and rummaged out a '''loaf''' of dry bread and some hardtack.}}\n# Any [[solid]] block of [[food]], such as [[meat]] or [[sugar]].\n#* {{RQ:Bacon Sylva Sylvarum|4|passage=sugar-'''loaf'''}}\n# {{lb|en|Cockney rhyming slang}} {{ellipsis of|en|loaf of bread}}: the [[brain]] or the [[head]].<ref>{{R:GDoS|id=lueucni|entry=loaf (of bread)|pos=n}}</ref>\n#: {{syn|en|q=slang|bonce|noddle|nut|Thesaurus:head}}\n#: {{co|en|[[use one's loaf|use one's '''loaf''']]}}\n#* {{RQ:Wodehouse Jeeves in the Offing|chapter=VIII and XII|passage=It is frequently said of Bertram Wooster that he is a man who can think on his feet, and if the necessity arises he can also use his '''loaf<!--(as \"brain\")-->''' when on all fours. [...]<!--ch. XII--> “Why didn't the idiot tell her not to open it?” “It was his first move. ‘I've found a letter from you here, precious,’ she said. ‘On no account open it, angel,’ he said. So of course she opened it.” She pursed the lips, nodded the '''loaf<!--(as \"head\")-->''', and ate a moody piece of crumpet. “So that's why he's been going about looking like a dead fish.”}}\n# A solid block of [[soap]], from which standard [[bar soap]] is [[cut]].\n# {{lb|en|cellular automata}} A particular [[still life]] configuration with seven living [[cell]]s.\n#* {{quote-newsgroup|en|date=1989-11-20|author=Dean Hickerson|title=Life: glider gun origin|newsgroup=comp.theory.cell-automata|url=https://groups.google.com/g/comp.theory.cell-automata/c/kL6pRsRDG4Q/m/jyweN_cOzTgJ|text=It runs for 17331 generations before stabilizing as 136 blinkers, 109 blocks, 65 beehives, 18 '''loaves''', 18 boats, 7 ships, 4 tubs, 3 ponds, 2 toads, and 40 gliders.}}\n#* {{quote-newsgroup|en|date=1992-09-10|author=David Bell|title=Spaceships in Conway's Life (Part 3b)|newsgroup=comp.theory.cell-automata|url=https://groups.google.com/g/comp.theory.cell-automata/c/WNVmyQYN0EQ/m/LJulQ32mFWcJ|text=Running a LWSS into it can produce various debris. One of these reactions produces a '''loaf'''. When the '''loaf''' is properly hit with other LWSSs, it can be pulled backwards.}}\n#* {{quote-newsgroup|en|date=1998-01-27|author=Ian Osgood|title=Life: looking for smallest ancestor of a quad-loaf|newsgroup=comp.theory.cell-automata|url=https://groups.google.com/g/comp.theory.cell-automata/c/jAV2m1Ds86E/m/chr7Ia-PjYcJ|text=I am looking for the smallest ancestor of the following four '''loaf''' pattern in Conway's Game of Life:}}\n# {{lb|en|informal|slang}} A [[catloaf]].\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|en|barracouta loaf\n|catloaf\n|catloafed\n|confinement loaf\n|cottage loaf\n|disciplinary loaf\n|Dutch loaf\n|farmhouse loaf\n|farthing loaf\n|flesh loaf\n|fleshloaf\n|foodloaf\n|French loaf\n|frosted ribbon loaf\n|granary loaf\n|half a loaf is better than no bread\n|half a loaf is better than no loaf\n|half a loaf is better than none\n|liverloaf\n|loaf bread\n|loaflet\n|loaflike\n|loaf of bread\n|loaf pan\n|loaf sugar\n|malt loaf\n|meatless loaf\n|meatloaf,meat loaf\n|nut loaf\n|olive loaf\n|pan-loaf\n|pimento loaf\n|pinch a loaf\n|plain loaf\n|Pullman loaf\n|ribbon loaf\n|sandwich loaf\n|sugar loaf,sugar-loaf\n|tank loaf\n|tea loaf\n|temse loaf\n|Vienna loaf\n|wave loaf\n}}\n\n=====Descendants=====\n{{top3}}\n* {{desc|bn|লোফ|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|mh|ļoob|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|nb|loff|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|nn|loff|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|gd|lofa|bor=1}}\n{{bottom}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|block of bread}}\n* Arabic: {{t|ar|رَغِيف|m}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|самун|m}}, {{t+|bg|хляб|m}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|fogassa|f}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t|cmn|一條麵包|tr=yī tiáo miànbāo}}\n* Cornish: {{t|kw|torth|f}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|bochník|m}}, {{t+|cs|pecen|m}}\n*: Old Czech: {{t|zlw-ocs|bochnec|m}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|brood|n}}\n* Esperanto: {{t+check|eo|bulo}}\n* Estonian: {{t|et|päts}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|leipä}}, {{t+|fi|limppu}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|baguette|f}}, {{t+|fr|miche|f}}, {{t+|fr|pain|m}}\n* Galician: {{t|gl|bolo|m}}, {{t|gl|molete|m}}, {{t|gl|sembra|f}}, {{t|gl|panocha|f}}, {{t|gl|tarxa|f}}, {{t|gl|regueifa|f}}, {{t|gl|fogaza|f}}\n* Georgian: {{t|ka|ბატონი}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Laib|m}}, {{t|de|Laib Brot|m}}, {{t+|de|Brot|n}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|καρβέλι|n}}, {{t+|el|φρατζόλα|f}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{t|grc|ἄρτος|m}}\n* Hawaiian: {{t|haw|pōpō}}\n* Hebrew: {{t+|he|כיכר|tr=kikár}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|kenyér}}\n* Icelandic: {{t|is|hleifur|m}}, {{t+|is|brauð|n}}\n* Ingrian: {{t|izh|bulkka}}\n* Irish: {{t|ga|bairín|m}}, {{t|ga|bollóg|f}}, {{t|ga|builín|m}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|pagnotta|f}}, {{t|it|pan carrè|m}}, {{t|it|pane in cassetta|m}}\n* Japanese: {{t|ja|[[パン]][[一]][[塊]]|tr=pan hito katamari}}, {{t|ja|[[パン]][[一]][[斤]]|tr=pan ikkin}}\n* Kazakh: {{t|kk|бөлке}}\n* Latin: {{t+|la|pānis|m}}\n* Latvian: {{t|lv|kukulis}}, {{t+|lv|klaips|m}}\n* Macedonian: {{t|mk|ве́кна|f}}, {{t|mk|сому́н|m}}\n* Malay: {{t+|ms|buku}}\n* Māori: {{t-check|mi|rohi}}\n* Old Church Slavonic: {{t|cu|хлѣбъ|m}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|bochenek|m}}, {{t+|pl|bochen|m}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|pão|m}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|pâine|f}}, {{t+|ro|franzelă|f}}, {{t+|ro|jimblă|f}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|буха́нка|f}}, {{t+|ru|бу́лка|f}}, {{t+|ru|бато́н|m}}\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{t|gd|lof|m}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{t|sh|вѐкна|f}}, {{t|sh|векница|f}}, {{t|sh|хле̏б|m}}, {{t|sh|хље̏б|m}}, {{t|sh|штру̏ца|f}}\n*: Latin: {{t+|sh|vèkna|f}}, {{t+|sh|veknica|f}}, {{t+|sh|hlȅb|m}}, {{t+|sh|hljȅb|m}}, {{t+|sh|štrȕca|f}}\n* Slovene: {{t|sl|hleb|m}}, {{t|sl|hlebec|m}}, {{t|sl|štruca|f}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|pan|m}}, {{t+|es|hogaza|f}}\n* Swahili: {{t+|sw|mkate|c3|c4}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|limpa|c}}\n* Tagalog: {{t-needed|tl}}\n* Taos: {{t|twf|pʼȍkúna}}\n* Welsh: {{t+|cy|torth|f}}\n* Yiddish: {{t|yi|לעבל|n}}, {{t|yi|לאַבן|m}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|block of food}}\n* Cornish: {{t|kw|torth|f}}\n* Estonian: {{t|et|päts}}, {{t|et|latt}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|mureke}} {{qualifier|minced meat}}; {{t+|fi|toppa}} {{qualifier|sugar}}, {{t+|fi|kimpale}}\n* Hawaiian: {{t-needed|haw}}\n* Icelandic: {{t|is|hleifur|m}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|pan|m}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|head (''slang'')}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|testa|f}}\n* Estonian: {{t|et|kupp}}, {{t+|et|kaalikas}}, {{t+|et|nupp}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|polla}}\n* Italian: {{t|it|capoccia|f}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|коча́н|m}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|mollera|f}}, {{t+|es|testa|f}} {{qualifier|slang}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|large block of soap}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|barra|f}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|tanko}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|savonnette|f}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|panetto|m}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|barra|f}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|barra|f}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n=====References=====\n<references/>\n* (soap) Miller, J.L. \"Customers believe in downstate Soap Fairy\", ''[[Wikipedia:Delaware News-Journal|The News Journal]]'', B10, January 10, 2006.\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|Cockney rhyming slang}} To [[headbutt]]\n\n===Etymology 2===\nProbably a {{back-form|en|loafer|nocap=3}}.\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To do nothing, to be [[idle]].\n#: {{ux|en|'''loaf''' about, '''loaf''' around}}\n#* '''2015,''' {{w|Elizabeth Royte}}, ''Vultures Are Revolting. Here’s Why We Need to Save Them.'', National Geographic (December 2015)[https://web.archive.org/web/20151213095110/http://ngm.nationalgeographic.com/2016/01/vultures-text]\n#*: They don’t (often) kill other animals, they probably form monogamous pairs, and we know they share parental care of chicks, and '''loaf''' and bathe in large, congenial groups.\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{l|en|idle}}, {{l|en|laze}}, {{l|en|lounge}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col2|en|loaf about|loaf around}}\n\n=====Descendants=====\n* {{desc|nn|loffe|bor=1}}\n* {{desc|sv|luffa|bor=1}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|do nothing}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|безделнича}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|gandulejar}}\n* Cherokee: {{t|chr|ᎡᏙᎵᏙᎭ}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|zahálet}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|niksen}}, {{t+|nl|rondlummelen}}\n* Estonian: {{t|et|logelema}}, {{t|et|laisklema}}, {{t|et|vedelema}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|maleksia}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|paresser}}\n* German: {{t|de|nichts tun}}, {{t+|de|herumlungern}}, {{t|de|rumhängen}} {{qualifier|colloquial}}, {{t+|de|faulenzen}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|τεμπελιάζω}}, {{t+|el|κοπροσκυλιάζω}}, {{t+|el|λουφάρω}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{t|grc|ῥαθυμέω}}\n* Icelandic: {{t+|is|slóra}}\n* Irish: {{t|ga|[[bheith]] [[ag]] [[leadaíocht]] ([[thart]])}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|oziare}}, {{t+|it|bighellare}}, {{t+|it|girovagare}}, {{t+|it|vagabondare}}, {{t|it|trastullarsi}}\n* Latvian: {{t|lv|slaistīties}}\n* Macedonian: {{t|mk|де́нгуби}}, {{t|mk|безде́лничи}}\n* Māori: {{t|mi|ānewanewa}}, {{t|mi|kaweka}}, {{t|mi|whakapāeko}}, {{t|mi|whakapateko}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|bimbać|impf}} {{qualifier|colloquial}}, {{t+|pl|przebimbać|pf}} {{qualifier|colloquial}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|vadiar}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|trândăvi}}, {{t+|ro|lenevi}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|бездельничать|impf}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|holgazanear}}, {{t|es|estar a la bartola}}, {{t+|es|golfear}}\n* Turkish:\n*: Ottoman Turkish: {{t|ota|تنبللنمك|tr=tembellenmek}}\n* Welsh: {{t|cy|diogi}}, {{t+|cy|stelcian}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=aflo|AFOL|Olaf|foal}}\n\n{{cln|en|nouns with irregular plurals}}\n{{C|en|Cats|Food and drink}}"}}